The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Metro | Writers building
                                                                                                                         3                                                                                      Writers building
                              The oval table belonged to Vidyasagar; the chairs around it have not yet been labelled                    The Krishna Kirtan punthi, preserved in a wooden case                            
	Bangiya Sahitya Parishad has thrown open the doors of its literary museum, Sahityik Sagar Kaksha, to the public. Housed on the first floor of the building at 243/1 APC Road, the museum covering an area of 3,500sq ft has been set up with a grant of Rs 20 lakh from the Heritage Corpus Fund of the Calcutta Municipal Corporation.                   This exquisitely wood-carved chair was used by Bankim Chandra; another ornate chair on display belonged to poet Nabin Chandra Sen. The two pieces are the museums top draws. Pictures by Bishwarup Dutta      
	Metro takes a walk through the museum.      
	A glass panel displaying the relics of and items used by Raja Rammohun Roy, Iswarchandra Vidyasagar and Bankim Chandra Chattopadhyay. The exhibits include Rammohuns death mask, a lock of his hair and his famous turban.        
	Among Vidyasagars articles are his Government Sanskrit College certificate and the manuscript of his collection of Bengali words. The Bankim treasures include his turban and an inkpot                                                                                                                                                                
